# Tricorne Licensing

Tricorne is a **multi-license project**. Different kinds of artifacts carry
different licenses because a distribution is a bundle of different kinds of
work. See `DESIGN.md` §11 and `CLAUDE.md` §3.5 for the governance rationale.

## Quick reference

| Artifact class                                      | License                | SPDX ID              |
|-----------------------------------------------------|------------------------|----------------------|
| Packaging (RPM specs, kickstarts, build scripts)    | MIT                    | `MIT`                |
| Original code (`engage/`, Purple Corner tooling)    | Apache License 2.0     | `Apache-2.0`         |
| SELinux policy modules (`selinux/`)                 | GNU GPL v2 or later    | `GPL-2.0-or-later`   |
| Artwork, logos, wallpapers (`artwork/`)             | CC BY-SA 4.0 †         | `CC-BY-SA-4.0`       |
| Documentation (`docs/`, `*.md`)                     | CC BY-SA 4.0           | `CC-BY-SA-4.0`       |
| Upstream packaged tools (inside tarballs)           | Upstream-owned         | (see each spec file) |

† Artwork is subject to a trademark carve-out: the "Tricorne" name and the
tricorne logo marks remain trademarks of **Thread & Signal LLC**. The CC-BY-SA
license grants broad rights to the *content* of the artwork files, not to the
trademarks. See `TRADEMARK.md`.

## How the licenses are organized

Each license's full text lives in the [`LICENSES/`](LICENSES/) directory as a
plain-text file named by its SPDX identifier
(`LICENSES/Apache-2.0.txt`, `LICENSES/MIT.txt`, etc.). This follows the
[REUSE Specification v3](https://reuse.software/spec/), which Fedora
packaging is moving toward.

Every source file Tricorne authors carries an SPDX header declaring the
license that applies to it. For example:

```text
# SPDX-FileCopyrightText: 2026 Thread & Signal LLC
# SPDX-License-Identifier: Apache-2.0
```

Markdown files place the header inside an HTML comment:

```text
<!--
SPDX-FileCopyrightText: 2026 Thread & Signal LLC
SPDX-License-Identifier: CC-BY-SA-4.0
-->
```

Run `reuse lint` at the repo root to verify that every file has a declared
license.

## Which license applies to which file

- Files under `packaging/`, `metapackages/`, `kickstart/`, `.github/workflows/`,
  and other build/CI configs → **MIT**
- Files under `engage/` and any other original code outside `selinux/` →
  **Apache-2.0**
- Files under `selinux/` (`.te`, `.fc`, `.if`) → **GPL-2.0-or-later**
- Files under `artwork/` → **CC-BY-SA-4.0** (plus trademark carve-out)
- Files under `docs/` and all `*.md` in the repo → **CC-BY-SA-4.0**
- Upstream tarballs pulled by spec files → each carries its own upstream
  license; the spec's `License:` tag reflects the installed contents

When a file's SPDX header disagrees with this summary, the SPDX header wins
and this file should be updated.

## Contributing

By contributing to Tricorne you agree that your contributions are licensed
under the license applicable to the file(s) you modify, per the table above.

Tricorne uses the [Developer Certificate of Origin](https://developercertificate.org/)
signed via `git commit -s`. There is no CLA. See `CONTRIBUTING.md`.

## Third-party licenses

When upstream tools are bundled into Tricorne RPMs, their upstream licenses
apply to their contents unchanged. Each spec file declares the upstream
license in the `License:` tag. Tricorne's spec file itself is MIT; the RPM
it builds carries whatever license its installed contents require.

